description.text: A cookie cutter in the shape of a peep.

This is a simple clip for attaching a kite string to a kite. You can tie the kite string to this, and then switch the clip between kites.

I recommend printing in ABS at 100% infill. No supports needed. You may need to sand a bit to fit your kite's string hole.

Uses and includes my Bezier library.

The kite string holder that I'm using is this one.

Resolution:

0.20

Infill:

100%

I looked at a clip in a commercial kite, and roughly followed its shape. I designed the curve directly in OpenSCAD. The BezierVisualize() module in my Bezier package let me adjust the curve node by node.

Initially, I used minkowski() to follow a narrow thread along the curve, but in an update switched to directly using hull() between spheres. The spheres are deliberately chosen to have $fn=6 which makes the overhangs acceptable for FDM printing.

Yeah, the ball tends to get stuck. Two issues- the ball will tend to break loose and start rocking, which means it will make contact with the cage uprights- after the ball is past the midway point vertically, things settle down. I haven't figured out how to deal with this- although increasing slightly the separation between the ball and the cage seems to help somewhat. What is needed is support material for the lower half of the ball, which winds up locking the ball to the cage anyway!
Secondly, unless one has the parameters zeroed in absolutely for the filament being used (extrusion temperature, extrusion rate, retraction, etc.), there will likely be stringing, which is going to tie the ball to the columns at the corners. description.text:
Hello! For my senior project, I have designed devices to assist people in playing musical instruments. As seen in the attached pictures, the device has a modular base, which allows it to be paired with interchangeable drumstick, xylophone mallet, or guitar pick holders. The device straps onto the user's forearm, which will ultimately assist people with limited grasping ability in their hands to experience the power of playing a musical instrument.

General info:

Extra Materials:

  • M5 Screws
    -- 2 M5 Screws (12 mm in length) for base/plate of device to connect with holders
    -- 1 M5 Screw (12 mm in length) for drumstick and xylophone mallet holders to act as a set screw
    -- 1 M5 Screw (16 mm in length) for guitar pick holder to act as a set screw
  • M5-0.8 Hex Nuts
    --2 Hex Nuts per base/plate
    --1 Hex Nut for holders
  • Velcro: 0.75 in. or 19.05 mm wide straps (2 per device)

There are 3 sizes of the device available from the files above. The size is determined by the width of the middle of the user's forearm laid on a flat surface.

  • Small Plate for Prosthetic (Small Size): 4.32 cm or less (1.7 in. or less)
  • Plate for Prosthetic with Fillet (Medium Size): 6.35 cm or less (2.5 in. or less)
  • Large Plate for Prosthetic (Large Size): 7.62 cm or less (3 in. or less)
    -- All of the designs include a fillet; these are just the names that correspond with the given files.

There are also three types of drumstick holders.There is a standard size chart for drumsticks, and the specific size should be labeled on most brand name sticks. However, you can just measure the diameter of your drumstick to find out which drumstick holder best suits your own.

  • New 0.59 inch Drumstick Holder (0.59 in or 1.5 cm in diameter): Fits sizes 5A and 7A
  • New 0.63 inch Drumstick Holder (0.63 in or 1.6 cm in diameter): Fits sizes 1A, 3A, 5B
  • New 0.68 inch Drumstick Holder (0.68 in or 1.7 cm in diameter): Fits sizes 2B, Rock

The Xylophone Mallet Holder will hold any mallet that doesn't have a diameter over 0.5 inches or 1.27 centimeters.
The Guitar Pick Holder will hold most standard guitar picks.

Total Time for Completion:

  • Drumstick and Xylophone Mallet Holders: Around 1.5 hours
  • Guitar Pick Holder: Around 1.5 Hours
  • Small Plate for Prosthetic: Around 2.5 hours
  • Plate for Prosthetic with Fillet: Around 3 hours
  • Large Plate for Prosthetic: Around 3.5 hours

PRINTING INSTRUCTIONS: All of these files require a M5-0.8 hex nut to the be inserted into the design at a specific time during the print. See print settings below for details.

Please feel free to comment and/or ask questions!

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator (5th Generation)

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Infill:

10%

Notes:

As stated in the summary, each design requires a hex nut to be inserted during the printing process. Below are the heights and percentages at which you should pause the print for each file.

  • Small Plate for Prosthetic: Height = 21.49 mm, Percentage = Around 76% completion
  • Plate for Prosthetic with Fillet: Height = 28.65 mm, Percentage = Around 79% completion
  • Large Plate for Prosthetic: Height = 33.60 mm, Percentage = Around 80% completion
  • All Drumstick and Xylophone Mallet Holders: Height = 40.77 mm, Percentage = Around 80% completion
  • Guitar Pick Holder: Height = 41.38 mm, Percentage = Around 80% completion

Some 3D printers have a Z Pause Height Function, which allows the user to program the printer to stop at a specific height during the print. If your printer has this function, I highly suggest using it, as you won't have to keep track of the progress of your print. Having or not having a raft should not significantly affect the pausing heights I stated above.

If your printer does not have a Z Pause Height Function, then you will have to monitor your print and manually pause it at the correct moment in order to insert the hex nut.

Printers are not uniform across brands and models, thus the heights and percentages I gave may not be exactly the same during your print. Ultimately, the goal is to have the hex nut encased by the print, so use your best judgement as to when to place the hex nut in the design.

The prints should be oriented so that the "fins" on the holder are at the bottom and the plates look like an upside-down "U". See the attached picture at the top for a reference.

In addition, the layer height should be set to 0.2 mm

Post-Printing for Drumstick, Xylophone Mallet, or Guitar Pick Holder

The design for all of the holders include "fins" which act as supports on one side of the model. These can be easily snapped off and filed down once the print has finished.

1: Print 4 corners and a center section in your choice of colors and materials. PLA may soften if you have hot motors. ABS works well. I'm sure PETG and Nylon would be fine choices as well.

title: YAFSH - Yet Another Filament Spool Holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The end table that I am using as a home base for my Tevo Tarantula has a unique under-surface - modeled so eloquently in the last photo - that prohibits most clamp-type holders. There just isn't enough room to provide a stable grip. So, drawing on my years of woodworking experience, I fashioned a clip-type clamp - say that three times fast! This clips over the lower rail to hold the unit in place and holds a small, old mailing tube as a spool holder.

I know this is probably a one-off, unique situation, so I am including the SketchUp STL file for you to modify as needed for your table.

Printer:

Tevo Tarantula

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

Enable supports everywhere for the clamp to accommodate the mounting hole, but supports touching the build plate are enough for the braces and the uprights. You will need to print two of each part for a complete system. Some filing/sanding made be necessary due to printer (in)accuracy.

These were designed for a snug fit, but a little glue (I used Duco cement) will help greatly with stability. There is a small amount of wiggle room in my design which is taken up by a thin piece of leather to prevent table marring.

description.text:
Somewhere in the deep of the web , i've found a user, he experimented with the OMRON EE SPY 402. After reading the manual i decided quickly to buy one ( and two more for friends).
Please read the manual and technical details from here.
(https://www.ia.omron.com/products/family/440/specification.html)

The main feature are: Modulated active IR-Sensor. short distance. 5V and NPN that means it could be direct wired to original z-switch connectors
Accidentally i orderd a used one ([email protected] from 5-50€), but a little bit diffrent type EE SPY 412. I got mine for 8Euros on ebay.

Please read the manual and technical details from here.
(https://www.ia.omron.com/products/family/443/specification.html)
The main feature are also : modulated avtive IR-Sensor. short Distance. 5V and NPN and very light weighted.

This is for users with autolevel enabled firmware (I'm a skynet user) . Do all the steps that described in Web to enable autolevel.
(https://3dprint.wiki/reprap/anet/a8/improvement/autobedleveling)

If you use M119 to test the triggering use white paper and look to the buildin LED!!! Triggering on glass bed results in a short flash around a hotspot.

You need one plug from type: JST XHP-3
(https://www.amazon.de/S%C3%A4tze-2-5-3-Pin-Stecker-Stecker-Draht-Buchse/dp/B01DU9OS5K/ref=sr_1_fkmr0_1?s=toys&ie=UTF8&qid=1491909206&sr=1-1-fkmr0&keywords=JST+XH+2.5+3-P
or
https://www.amazon.de/gp/product/B01DU87NT4/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
)

Instead of use a capazitive,induktive or mechanical sensor you can plug this sensor direct to the ( all the three wires) board.
You didn't need a octocoupler or the two resitors and no additonal 12V needed. Almost just Plug&Play.
Wiring is very easy. Solder 3 small wire (lenght each arround 1m) to the sensor and be careful with temperature (quick with a small solder iron).

Ground to Ground(-); 5V to VCC(+); and Out to Signal. Look here for wiring:
https://3dprint.wiki/reprap/anet/a8/improvement/autobedleveling)

I designed a very easy sensor mount. It's equipped with plasic dowels, which fit in the (non-threaded) holes on the lower rear of the slides without screws.
You only need 2x M3 screws and nuts for the sensor to mount .
The nozzle should to be below (1-3mm) the sensor.

I attach my configuration.h from "skynet" . The offset of sensor is X 18mm & Y 45mm

Use at your own risk, be careful and keep hands on the powerswitch while testing :-)

I use the sensor with glass, buildtak, fr4 and carbon bed. No problem at all yet.

description.text:
Blender file included for those who know how to use subdivision and displacement modifiers with textures, UV unwrapping is useful too.

You can get free (with attribution) patterns at www.freepik.com for example.

EggXXX.stl files are whole eggs. EggXXX_X.stl files are two halves with a domino joint. Use icluded domino.stl for printing the (half)domino with the tolerance (tightness) you want and domino_cavity.stl for making the hole in the model.

UPDATE: It seems that printing a whole egg upright with meshmixer + slicer supports although yields an ugly bottom, needs less time with post-processing (sanding and filling imperfections)

For Blender: Set subdivision to preview level 4 for working. Play with displacement settings and textures to find what you like. Bump the subdivisions to 5 or 6 (for those who like it to the max) and when exporting to STL select "Apply modifiers" in left side. Then fire up meshmixer > transform > change the dimensions to whatever you want (I do 55 for long edge to get a M~L sized egg). Then CTRL+A to select entire ebject and SHIFT+R to go into reduction tool. I find that 80-85% reduction is the best. Apply, export and overwrite your old file. Now you have an egg, sized properly and not killing your PC with millions of triangles.

How to do the "DOMINO" joints. In meshmixer take a domino cavity file and drag it in and "append". Apply transparent shader to the egg so you can see the cavity. Select the cavity from the object browser, orient and place it in the middle where you will be cutting. Select both and combine. Use plane cut tool to slice keeping both halves. Separate shells and export each as an individual file.

description.text: create bolw

Design goal was been a easy-to-print 2x2x2. And, at design-start I didn't had found annother 2x2x2 here (It was been, but the search function here didn't found. If you are google 'www.thingiverse.com rubik 2x2x2' there is annother.

Step 1:
Print the calibrate cube, check if your machine is good. If your measurement is scaled (multiplied) in X and Y then it is ok. If the outline is bigger and the hole is smaller, you have to adjust this in your slicing software. slic3r 1.2.9 and repsnapper provide adjustment parameter. If your slicer doesn't provide this parameter, switch over to annother slicer. I mean, because of the screws the design will tolerate some mismatchs.

Step 2:
Do not rotate the STL. Slice in the same rotation as shown. No support material required, slice without support. (except mid.stl; this may need support)
Print it. Because of the small footprint, maybe you have to use additional glue on printbed. I have stabilized with ABS-juice after 5mm Z-Height.
Sandpaper it, remove all blobs.
PLA: sandpaper it very very carefully.
ABS: I have printed in ABS and acetone vaporized. I have made some test prints in ABS and PLA (with annother design), ABS+vaporization is a much better way for twisty things. If your machine takes PLA only then use PLA.

Step 3: paint the outsides (or sticker it). Because of recommended grease it is better to paint before.

Step 4: Assembly: Add the M3 nylock nut to the position, come with a M3 rod thru the mid and catch the nut. Pull the nut into the core and thru the center of the core. Unscrew the rod and change immediately to the M3 screw. If get lost inside the core it is hard to catch again. Continue assembly. Don't forget grease. I recommend Vaseline. Because I don't have, I take standard ball bearing grease.

Use 220x220x10 Cork from a pinwall. Cut off a little square from 10x10 on each corner.

Very important !!! Use at your on risk :-)

Don't level the bed to low. The Y-Motor or bed could be damaged
or you have to cut of the cork in the shape of the Y-Motor. After install use your hand to slide the bed on the Y-Axis.

description.text:
This thing is more about printable threads than a turnbuckle. Print without support, it's all in the geometry! In a nutshell : M10 printed male and female threads that are printed horizontally for extra strength and better print resolution. Most printers have better XY resolution than Z so this has the advantage of:
  • They are not subject to the 45deg rule so true threads can be created which are compatible with their metallic counterparts..
  • The layer orientation means they are particularly stronger and less prone to layer de-lamination.
  • Longer length of thread due to more stable print heights.
    • http://www.gyrobot.co.uk
    http://www.facebook.com/gyrobotuk

Print without support, it's all in the geometry!   
For this turnbuckle, each end has a right hand (RH) and a left hand (LH) metric M10 thread. The left hand thread is denoted by the letter "L" in the stl model and "LH" in the filename. This means you turn in opposite direction to conventional threads.  
You can change the length of the turnbuckle by rotating the inner buckle clockwise or anticlockwise in relation to the ends.  
You can print either the eyelet or hook ends  for RH or LH threads.  
I have supplied two buckle stl files, one has extra thread clearance should your printer's calibration or flow rate print too tight. You might want to clean the threads up by running a metal nut or bolt through the threads to clean up any oozing or print defects.  
Finally, a little lubrication helps the threads run smoothly too.

The original Prusa is designed to have a 25mm Nylon nut, but I haven´t been able to fit one. But this will do the trick.
In case you prefer to use the normal end stops, I added the design for this as well.
The x-end-idler-brass-nut-stl on the other side should of course work in both cases.

While upgrading (I crashed my PINDA into the heat-bed and broke the plastic part that holds the probe) my MK2 to the MK2s. I did fortunately print the MK2s parts earlier on.
I saw that the Nylon nut now goes inside the X-end pieces (did I do that wrong before??)

description.text:
[Edit - Customizer fixed]
There are several designs for woodworking tools to make chopsticks. This is one - but printed in PLA instead of made in wood. Derived from this Instructable - which is quite cool IMHO.

  • https://www.instructables.com/id/Customized-Chopstick-Maker/step5/The-Sled/
  • https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UsKm8szXOq0

So this one is made of three main printed pieces - the template block, the plane block, and a guide for positioning the finished chopstick to plane the prism onto the end.

This object also requires a metal threaded rod (with nuts) to keep it all compressed together. A metal washer needs to be put on the end to act as an end stop to hold the chopstick while you plane it.
The washer needs to be filed so that the plane can move smoothly along the guides. You might want to print the washer 3d model out to use as a template when cutting and filing.

The tool can be customized to make chopsticks of varying length and varying taper.

User chooses:

  • length of sticks,
  • desired start and end diameters (taper)
  • angle of end cut (30, 45, ??)
  • amount of tolerance in initial blank for first cut operation (i.e. what size pieces will you start with)

Instructions:

  • Assuming a taper from 7mm end to 5mm head (actually adjustable in customizer)

Side1

  • planes oversize blank to 7mm thickness
  • user rotates blank by 90 and so planes two adjacent sides to get to 7mm

Side2

  • puts taper onto two sides
  • goes from 7-6mm
  • user planes first two adjacent sides of blank

Side3

  • puts taper onto the other two sides
  • goes from 7mm to 5mm final resulting in equal taper on all sides
  • user planes remaining two adjacent sides of blank to final taper

Side4

  • v cut to bring into octagonal shape approximating round
    • (can be further smoothed by sanding)
  • user planes all four diagonals of the blank

Prism end cut

  • end cut does diamond shape at handle end of chopstick
  • user attaches guide and inserts chopstick through top plate guide
    • use an offcut of chopstick on the side, through the hole, to jam the chopstick and guide holder in a vice.
  • cuts and rotates 4 times to get pointed (octagonal) end

Lengths:

  • typically 210mm to 270mm, cooking chopsticks are longer (30-40cm).

chinese - (kuaizi) longer (270) and thicker - do not taper as much as other two.
korean - (jeotgarak, sujeo-with spoon) toughest and heaviest of them all. Medium taper.
Japanese - (hashi-eating, ryoribashi-cooking, saibashi-serving)

  • shortest, tapers more than others, taper closer to the end.
  • can be ribbed near tip to grab fish.
  • 23cm male, 21cm female, 30cm cooking.

"Perfect length" for a specific person is 1.5 times the distance between tip of your extended thumb and forefinger.
To make the plane guide work smoothly - sand the guide surfaces lightly and then apply wax to them. This way the guide will be easy to move and give good results.

Assuming I get vocal interest in these mods, I might do a second version of this with an alignment collar 20mm from the chamfered end of the adapter so you can ensure it''s jammed in the barrel straight. Or you can take the information I just gave you and do it yourself as a remix. EDIT: Done. Added with and without support. Reduced poly count for convenience.

Considering how much power it takes to fire a Mega dart, and that all of that power is now used with a projectile that is about half the size, the range and speed is unbelievable. However, they are still very prone to swerve due to environmental changes and the like... It's still Nerf, folks, the projectile has ALWAYS been the problem of long range accuracy.

Still thinking about different mods for this piece. The thing that has me stumped right now is how to gum up the secondary AR in the Bigshock... Anybody familiar with this issue is free to comment.

Hi, this is my solution for hot end air cooling for Solidoodle 2. I wanted to avoid adding too much weight to the print head, as well as mess with wiring and need for extensive modifications of the print head. I used bigger aquarium pump (pictured) because it delivers a bit more air than smaller ones. I used flexible modular hose that you can be downloaded from Thingiverse http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9006 . I printed five segments and nozzle. The great thing about this modular hose that standard air hose for aquarium fits right in and I pushed it almost all the way through entire length of all five segments. No alteration needed!
I had to design my own bracket that you can download. It will hold Loc-line segment on its own (designed to snap-on) but I secured bend and all joints with hot glue so I can print on higher speeds. Best thing to do is to print all parts (lic-line/nozzle/bracket) at once. So plastic will time to harden on a vertical part of bracket.
Designed bracket snaps on the print head by itself, (on heads of preexisting bolts) but I used super strong magnets to keep it attached for added security. There is a place that sells smaller quantities of N52 grade magnets which are perfect for this kind of application. http://www.ebay.com/usr/forcefielddesigns
Assembly is very simple and not intrusive. Not tools required! Snap bracket on bolts heads; secure it with magnets; snap modular house to bracket; bend to desired position, secure with hot glue (advised) and you ready to go! If need to take off - remove magnets, and pull all construction away. That's it! This design handles fairly fast movements and delivers air exactly to the tip of nozzle preventing sagging on overhangs.
Sorry for not very clean prints - I'll clean raft later - just finish printing and assembly and was checking how it all will work.
Thank you! Have fun! UPDATE: New version (Mark 2) will work with just 4 segments of flexible hose (plus nozzle) and will go under frame of solidoodle. First design would limit Y axis move by bumping into the case frame (I discover it during calibration - this issue never manifested itself during prints). As a result new design is smaller and lighter. P.S. check out video of this Thing in action at: http://youtu.be/Es_axKm0ZFs

comments.text: Hi, Solidoodler! It is common believe that for high quality prints cooling plastic on exit of hot end is absolutely essential. I would agree - without cooling on overhangs plastic would curl up and create all types of problems. As for best design for cooling system - I am limited by construction of Solidoodle - moving heavy head with extruder, motor, hot end, fan (creating centrifugal resistance) is challenge on its own. This why I tried to keep it as light as possible and without moving parts that would resist rapid movements of the head. I am still experimenting with my design and thinking about joining two aquarium pumps to get steadier and stronger stream of air. Subjectively - it works, but I don't have any way to quantify change in quality. More experiments are on its way and I will post results if it will be something interesting! Thank you for looking!
